Make a Debian package for the Checker Framework, with a javacheck alias.  Maybe start with Daikon, to warm up.
Create a Debian package first; get a sponsor; and get it into Debian.
(After that, figure out how to get it into Ubuntu, may involve "syncing" to
make an Ubuntu package: https://wiki.ubuntu.com/SyncRequestProcess .)
Use the dh packaging helper, and the 3.0 (quilt) format
Do this setup:
http://packaging.ubuntu.com/html/getting-set-up.html

Use dh rather than debhelper.
pbuilder: https://wiki.ubuntu.com/PbuilderHowto

Look up how to do this.
Ubuntu packaging guide
  http://packaging.ubuntu.com/html/packaging-new-software.html
create a .deb Package from scripts or binaries
  http://askubuntu.com/questions/27715/create-a-deb-package-from-scripts-or-binaries
Tuturial slides; is useful (see especially slides 15ff):
  https://www.debian.org/doc/manuals/packaging-tutorial/packaging-tutorial.en.pdf
  (slide 45 is "Getting your package in Debian" -- use private repo first, I guess)
  (slide 60 is packaging a Java library; answers are later in the slide deck)
